Subject:    <a href="?t=95837886900044&r=1&w=2">overlapping domains and hosts</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837475100016&r=1&w=2">Larry Peterson &lt;llp () Purdue ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198503">1985-03-11 14:31:39</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426375&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426375&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Could someone shead light on the following issue? I am wondering
whether a site/domain name like "Purdue", which has several
subdomains, like CS, CC, etc. is both the name of a host (purdue is
currently a registered host), as well as the name of a domain. My
question has to do with identifying mail recipients with an address
of the form user@Purdue.EDU rather than user@merlin.cs.Purdue.EDU.
We are able to do this in the pe-domain world by pulling a trick --
we give one of our hosts the same name as our organization. Do we have
to pull this same trick in the domain world, or can we avoid naming
one of our hosts "purdue" and still support a name like user@purdue.edu?
The same question applies at lower levels. Can I send mail to
user@cs.purdue.edu without having to name one of my hosts cs.purdue?

The bottom line is this. Do domain names only support sending mail to
user@host.domain... (where I may give my host the same name as
my site), or does it support names of the form user@domain, where
I don't have a host named after my domain (at least not specifically,
I understand that the name server will return the Internet Address
of "some" host(s)).

Larry

